I have only very minor comments

I haven't seen `a \n < b`, only `a < \n b`, but I think that the later is bad, especially for inequalities.
```suggestion
  calc
    (1 + ‖x‖) ^ (finrank ℝ D + 1) * (‖x‖ ^ k * ‖f x‖)
      ≤ (1 + ‖x‖) ^ (finrank ℝ D + 1) * ((1 + ‖x‖) ^ k * ‖f x‖) := by gcongr; simp
    _ = (1 + ‖x‖) ^ (finrank ℝ D + 1 + k) * ‖f x‖ := by simp [pow_add]; ring
    _ ≤ C := hC x
```
I would assume that this is called `_root_.hasTemperateGrowth_zero`

With the new dot Lean 4 dot notation, it's better to put it in the namespace: when proving that something has temperate growth, then you can use `.zero` for `Function.HasTemperateGrowth.zero`, which turns out to be very nice. The library has not been updated everywhere to take advantage of this, but new lemmas should definitely take this form.
No, but `simp only [pow_add, mul_assoc]` does. I've made the change.

```suggestion
    Integrable (fun x ↦ ‖x‖ ^ k * ‖f x‖) μ := by
```
